        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Customer Returns Overview",
            Slug = "customer-returns-overview",
            Summary = "What customer returns (RMAs) are, the return lifecycle from Received to Closed, and how returns connect to sales orders, jobs, and inventory.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/customer-returns"]""",
            Tags = """["customer-returns","sales"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Customer Returns Overview\n\nCustomer Returns tracks goods a customer sends back, from the moment they arrive to the day the issue is closed. Every return is tied to the original job that made the goods, and optionally to a rework job created to fix the problem. Each return is called an RMA (Return Merchandise Authorization).\n\n### What Is a Customer Return?\n\nA return is goods a customer sends back because they are defective, made to the wrong specs, damaged in shipping, or fall short on quality. Each one gets its own RMA number (for example, RMA-00001) and moves through a set of stages until the issue is fully resolved and closed.\n\n### The Return Lifecycle\n\nA return moves through five stages in order:\n\n1. **Received** — You have logged the return. The goods have arrived back at your facility. This is the starting stage for a new return.\n2. **In Inspection** — Someone is inspecting the goods to find the root cause. The inspector and their findings are recorded.\n3. **Rework Ordered** — A rework job has been created to fix the defect. It appears on the board and follows the normal production flow. A return moves here automatically when you create the rework job while logging the return.\n4. **Resolved** — The issue has been handled — through rework, a replacement, a credit, or another fix. Mark the return resolved once that work is done.\n5. **Closed** — The final stage. The return is fully processed and closed out. Only resolved returns can be closed, and a closed return cannot be reopened or changed.\n\n### How Returns Connect to Other Features\n\n**Jobs:** Every return points back to the original job that produced the returned goods, so you always have full traceability. When you create a rework job, it links to the return and is also connected to the original job on the board.\n\n**Customers:** Each return is tied to the customer who sent the goods back. You can filter the list by customer to see all of that account's returns.\n\n**Sales Orders:** Returns are closely tied to the sales side. The goods first shipped on a sales order, and any replacement or credit may need a new order or an adjustment.\n\n**Rework Jobs:** When a return needs rework, the system can create a new job for you. Its title starts with '[Rework]', it uses the same track and operator as the original, it starts at the first production stage, and it comes in at High priority.\n\n### When to Use Customer Returns\n\n- A customer contacts you about defective or incorrect goods\n- Returned goods arrive at your facility and need to be logged\n- You need to track the inspection and resolution of a quality issue\n- Rework is needed and you want a linked production job for it\n- You need a record of every return for a customer or a job\n\n### Access and Permissions\n\nCustomer Returns is available to Admins, Managers, and Office Managers. The page gives you a searchable list with a status filter, a 'New Return' button that opens a form, and a detail panel where you resolve and close each return.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Process Walkthrough (Article) ────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Customer Returns — Process Walkthrough",
            Slug = "customer-returns-walkthrough",
            Summary = "A conceptual walkthrough of the customer return process: receiving a return, inspection, rework decisions, resolution, and closing.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 2,
            AppRoutes = """["/customer-returns"]""",
            Tags = """["customer-returns","sales","walkthrough"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Customer Returns — Process Walkthrough\n\nThis walkthrough follows a customer return from start to finish, from the moment the goods come back to the day you close it out. Every step happens on the Customer Returns page — the list, the New Return form, and the detail panel where you resolve and close.\n\n### Step 1: Receive the Return\n\nWhen a customer contacts you about sending goods back, start by logging a return. Click New Return and fill in:\n\n- **Customer** — Pick the customer sending the goods back.\n- **Original Job** — Choose the job that made the returned goods, so the return traces back to it.\n- **Reason** — Say why the goods are coming back (required). Be specific: 'Parts out of tolerance on bore diameter' beats 'Bad parts'.\n- **Notes** — Any extra context (optional): PO numbers, quantity returned, shipping details.\n- **Return Date** — When the goods came back, or are expected back.\n- **Create Rework Job** — Turn this on if you already know rework is needed, and the system creates a linked rework job for you.\n\nSaving generates the RMA number (for example, RMA-00001) and sets the stage to Received. If you asked for a rework job, the return starts at Rework Ordered instead, and the rework job appears on the board.\n\n### Step 2: Inspect the Returned Goods\n\nOnce the goods arrive, inspect them and record what you find. The return keeps track of who inspected it, when, and their findings. Note measurements, visible defects, and how the goods compare to the specs. These findings stay on the record for good and become part of the audit trail.\n\n### Step 3: Decide on Corrective Action\n\nBased on the inspection, decide how to make it right:\n\n- **Rework** — If the parts can be fixed, create a rework job (if you did not already in Step 1). It is a new production job titled with a '[Rework]' prefix, on the same track as the original, at High priority, and linked back to the original job.\n- **Replacement** — Start a new sales order and job to make replacement parts.\n- **Credit** — Issue a credit or adjust the invoice for the affected order.\n- **No Action** — If the return is not justified (customer error, shipping damage covered by insurance), note that in the return.\n\n### Step 4: Resolve the Return\n\nOnce the fix is done — rework finished, replacement shipped, or credit issued — mark the return resolved. This moves it to Resolved from wherever it is now.\n\n**Good to know:**\n- A return that is already Closed cannot be resolved.\n- You can resolve from any active stage. A return can go straight to Resolved without stopping at In Inspection or Rework Ordered first.\n\n### Step 5: Close the Return\n\nAfter the return is resolved and any follow-up is done, close it. This is the final stage and cannot be undone.\n\n**Good to know:**\n- Only resolved returns can be closed.\n- A closed return cannot be reopened, resolved again, or changed.\n- Resolving first, then closing, keeps the audit trail clean — once closed, the record is final.\n\n### Filtering and Reviewing Returns\n\nOn the list, use search and the status filter to find what you need. Filter by customer to see all of one account's returns, or by stage (Received, In Inspection, Rework Ordered, Resolved, or Closed) to focus on returns that still need action. The newest returns show first, and each row shows its RMA number, customer, original job, rework job (if any), stage, reason, and return date.\n\n### Best Practices\n\n1. **Log returns promptly** — Create the RMA as soon as the customer reports the issue, even before the goods arrive.\n2. **Be specific about the reason** — Vague reasons make it harder to spot patterns and improve quality.\n3. **Link rework jobs early** — If rework is likely, create the rework job while logging the return so it gets on the board sooner.\n4. **Inspect thoroughly** — Inspection findings are permanent and feed your quality trends.\n5. **Don't skip resolving** — Always resolve before you close, to keep the audit trail intact.\n6. **Review returns by customer** — Checking each customer's returns now and then helps you spot recurring quality issues.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Field Reference (QuickRef) ───────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Customer Returns Field Reference",
