            AppRoutes = """["/customer-returns"]""",
            Tags = """["customer-returns","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Who Works Returns, and Why\n\nCustomer Returns is a back-office and quality tool, so it is open to the people who own that work: Admins, Managers, and Office Managers. If you sign in as one of those, you can see the returns list, log a new return, edit it, inspect it, resolve it, and close it.\n\nEngineers and shop-floor operators do not open returns themselves. That is deliberate — the person on the floor should be looking at the job on the board, not sorting through customer paperwork. When a return needs rework, the app puts a rework job on the board for them, and that is all they touch. The RMA record, the reason, the inspection notes, and the customer conversation stay with the office. If the Returns page is missing from your menu, your install has this feature turned off; an admin can switch it on for you.\n\n## How RMA Numbers Are Assigned\n\nYou never type an RMA number. The app assigns it the moment you save the return, taking the last number it handed out and adding one — so RMA-00042 is followed by RMA-00043. The number is padded to five digits (RMA-00001, not RMA-1) so returns line up neatly when you sort or scan the list.\n\nNumbers are never reused. If a return is deleted, its number is retired with it — you will not see a fresh return quietly inherit an old number. That means a small gap in the sequence is normal and is not a sign anything is missing; it just tells you a return once existed there.\n\n## The Field Limits You'll Hit\n\nA few fields have length caps. They are generous, but worth knowing before you paste in a long customer email:\n\n- **Reason** is required and holds up to about 1,000 characters — roughly a solid paragraph. Enough for a clear, specific reason; not the place for the whole email thread.\n- **Notes** and **inspection notes** each hold up to about 2,000 characters — a couple of paragraphs. Use notes for context (PO numbers, quantities, who you spoke to) and inspection notes for what you actually found.\n- **Customer** and **original job** must each point at a real record that still exists. If you cannot find the job you expect in the picker, it may have been archived — check with whoever manages the board.\n\nWhen you edit a return later, you only touch the fields you change; everything you leave alone stays exactly as it was. So you can add a note months later without disturbing the original reason.\n\n## What the App Builds When You Order Rework\n\nTurning on 'Create Rework Job' does real work for you: it opens a production job and wires it back to the return, so nobody has to set one up by hand. Here is exactly what that job looks like when it lands on the board:\n\n- **Its own job number**, assigned in sequence just like any other job.\n- **A title that starts with [Rework]** followed by the original job's title — for example, '[Rework] Aluminum Housing Batch 5' — so it is obvious at a glance what it is.\n- **A description that names the RMA and the reason**, for example 'Rework for RMA-00003. Reason: Parts out of tolerance on bore diameter.' Anyone who opens the job on the board knows where it came from without hunting.\n- **The same production track as the original job**, starting at that track's first stage, so it flows the normal way.\n- **The same customer** as the return, and **the same person assigned** as the original job (if it had one).\n- **High priority**, because a customer is already unhappy and waiting.\n- **A link back to the original job**, so you can trace the pair from either side.\n\nAs soon as that job is created, the return itself moves to Rework Ordered and remembers which rework job belongs to it. From then on the floor works the job; you track the return.\n\n## Edge Cases Around Inspecting, Resolving, and Closing\n\nA few real-world situations come up often enough to spell out:\n\n- **A return can skip straight to Resolved.** There is no rule forcing it through inspection or rework first. If a customer reports a shipping mix-up and the fix is obvious, log it and resolve it — you do not have to march it through every stage.\n- **You cannot resolve a return that is already closed.** Closed is final. If you closed one by mistake, you cannot reopen it — log a fresh return that references the old RMA number in its reason, and note in the new one what happened.\n- **You can only close a return that has been resolved.** The app blocks any attempt to close one that is still open. That is what keeps the record honest: every closed return went through a real resolution, so a year from now the history holds up in a customer dispute or a quality audit.\n- **Inspection is recorded in three parts** — who inspected, when, and what they found — kept separate from the general notes so your quality findings do not get buried in shipping chatter. The natural moment to capture them is when you resolve, and once saved they stay on the record for good.\n- **Every meaningful step is timestamped in the activity history.** Logged, edited, resolved, closed — each is stamped with who did it and when, and none of it can be edited afterward. That is your trustworthy trail when you are piecing together how a recurring issue was handled across several returns.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Customer Returns training modules");
    }
